Please DO NOT follow the advice of this video. Nobody can tell if Mr. Veitch's stories are genuine or are just meant to amuse (which they do), but replying to actual scammers can destroy your email account, filling it with scam emails. This video makes it seem very enjoyable, but even if Mr. Veitch is telling the truth, he is surely doing so under controlled environment. Replying to a scam email, especially from a Gmail or Yahoo account will reveal your LOCATION (as in the city/town you live in), possibly even your FULL ADDRESS and your FULL NAME (that depends on the internet provider). You should NEVER respond to any scammers. This video and it's popularity has probably lead to many thousands of destroyed accounts (I speak from my own experience, sadly, as you might have guessed). Remember that like many channels on YouTube, Ted (and Mr. Veitch) are putting out these videos for views and profit, even if they do lead to suffering in the end.

Thank you for your time and please share this.

This is just silly and almost certainly 90% made up, although it may have elements of truth hidden in there, such as extracts from much longer mails.

I have - on several occasions - been bored enough to enter communication with some of these scammers. 

On one occasion I 'took over' the conversation between a Japanese girl in my office, who was brave enough to ask me if someone who was trying to get her to send money was genuine. To a non-native English speaker, the person she was talking to may have seemed on the up-and-up, but a look at just one sentence was sufficient to show that he wasn't the G.I. in Afghanistan he was claiming to be. I had quite a lot of fun pretending that I was sending him money and constantly getting his address or other information wrong on a transfer payment.

Another time, I persuaded a scammer in Hong Kong that I was going to give him an envelope with money in it in the lobby of the Peninsula Hotel (I was never within 1,000 km of Hong Kong). I sent the HK police a copy of the exchanges, but they never did anything about it.

I also had another scammer (who pretended to be a wealthy Iraqi lady who needed someone to help her get money out of the country) agree to 'meet' me at Heathrow Airport, to pick up the advance fee I was going to pay her. The scammer turned up, but of course I didn't.

And there were a few more.

However, there is one good piece of advice to take from James' piece, namely that if you're going to get involved in exchanges with potential scammers, make a special mail address to communicate from.

No, DON'T do this. You're inviting malware and scam/phishing URLs to be to you, and that's what you'll get. You're also verifying that your email address is live and active, resulting in it being added to 'Spam It' lists sold and traded around the Internet. IOW you'll multiply the amount of spam you get. Idiot 'script kiddy' scammers are one thing. But professional criminals are another. What I do is report everything to SpamCop.net. You're welcome. It's been laying waste to spammers since 1998. There are delightful interviews with spammers exclaiming expletives at SpamCop. Be an avenging angel. I also report all phishing email directly to the companies named in the spam. Most have an email address for forwarded phishing email. If they don't (hello Google), their loss.

True story: Had what I thought was a legit buyer for an item I was selling on Craigslist sending me a text saying hey, my dad's interested in buying, send him a message on how much you'll take for it at blah blah email. So I did. He said he was a business man out of the country at the moment, but his secretary could send a certified bank check of 1500.00. I said the item is only for 300.00. He said go ahead and cash the full amount, send a $1,000.00 back to him and I can keep the $500.00 with the extra being for my trouble. Orly? By this time I knew it was a scam, but I gave my address anyways to play along. The check showed up with a company logo on it as if it was his company's bank account, so I called the company. Sure enough, it was a scam. So I went back and forth for a couple of weeks with the guy stringing him along until finally I submitted everything to the police. Few weeks later I get a call from the FBI in the nearest big town from me saying they had all this stuff forwarded to them by the police. We got to laughing when he said "I see from the copies of all the emails you sent in that you were having a lot of fun with the guy, stringing him along" and I said yeah...wanted to see how far it would go. lol

When scammers ask for money I tell tell them I need the following information so I can transfer the money to them: 
"Your REAL name, the Name of your Bank, The bank address, your account number and bank routing number." 
 When they won't give me the info, I ask them..
" How can I send you money to YOUR bank account unless YOU give ME your banking information?? I'm NOT 'The Great and Exalted "O"..' and I can't ship you a pallet load of $100 dollar bills...I NEED your banking information."
 When they say we can do it by credit card, I say: "That's a REALLY complicated way to do it, but if that's the way you want to go, I'm OK with that.  I will then need your card number, expiration date and security code..Is it a Visa, Mastercard Discover or AmEx  card....You tell me your card info and I'll transfer the money to YOUR CARD and YOU can make the payment  from that."...NOW, will that be VIsa, Mastercard, Discover or AmEx???"
  If they are running the 'Your computer is infected' scam, I ask which computer they are talking about....That slows them up for a moment...They ask how many I have..I say I have : A Gamer computer, Video/graphics computer, An internet computer, My main frame, and my 3 laptops..( I can just about hear their eyes pop wide open as they invision all the money they think they are getting) tThey want typically want $99.95...  Then I say I  sure hope my NEW computer isn't infected...They say You have a New computer?  I say YES I just picked up a CRAY-9000 computer for dirt cheap...Have you ever seen a CRAY???  It's HUGE!! The size of a double wide Amana refrigerator....I can calculate multiple ballistic orbits on it, IN REAL TIME!!  The ONLY problem is that it takes about 3 weeks just to defragment the drives...If you can fix it for $99.95 then I'm all in...How ling do you figure it will take to run a virus scan on it...Oh yes, I almost forgot to mention, It's programmed in 'Pascal'......
.If they are still on the line at that point, I tell them they need an access code to hook into my CRAY...I tell them they have to type in EXACTLY what I type in and do it at the same time..If you're off by more than 1.25 seconds typing in the code the CRAY locks you out for 2 hours.....READY TO TYPE?? 
   Then I have them type in a code string that wipes out the 'media descriptor' on ALL hard drives, so NONE of the drives will identify to the BIOS...All that comes up on boot is: 'DRIVE NOT FOUND!".They are entering a Low Level DOS maintenance command  that writes DIRECTLY to the BIOS...TSR Program and it's a "legal' DOS command  so NO Anti-Virus program will see it. The ONLY way to remove it is to 're-burn' the BIOS.....When the scammer hits 'Enter' to 'launch access' He kills every hard drive hooked up to his system...It's 'technically legal' because you don't change ANY USER data on the drive..What IS erased is the data block that tells the BIOS.."I'm a W.D. Hard drive, 2.3 Tb, Sr#**********'  Without that 128 bits of data to send to the BIOS, the Hard drive doesn't exist...LOL

*Spoilers for The Hunger Games follow*

Once, I got an email from this company, because I took a random quiz about depression from them.
(I said my full name was "Yas Alyssa," because I didn't want them to know it, despite the fact that everyone who reads this will know my full name and probably already does) 
"Yas, need someone to talk to?"
Was the name of the email (I didn't actually read the rest of it)
Now, I had just finished the Hunger Games, so I actually did need someone to talk to, because I was really bored after doing freaking nothing but reading the Hunger Games.
But sanity is overrated, so I may have overexaggerated in my response (purposefully, of course)
My email is as follows:
"Yes, I do need somebody to talk to! I just finished the Hunger Games, and now I feel that life has no meaning! First of all, Katniss chose PEETA! I was on Team Gale! And she chose Peeta! I have hated Peeta for the entire series, and then Katniss married him! I feel so betrayed! I hate Susan Whats-her-face!¬†

Plus, the only thing I have been doing for the past month is read this series! Now it's over and I don't know what to do with myself!

And Prim died! And Finnick died! And Mags died! And RUE DIED! HOW CAN THEY DO THIS TO ME! PLEASE TALK TO ME! I HAVE BEEN BINGING FOR THE LAST HOUR AND I AM STILL SEVERELY DEPRESSED! PLEASE EMAIL ME BACK!"
(No, I don't hate Peeta. It's just a joke)

They, uh, just gave me an ad in response. Also, they learned my name. XD
"Hi Alyssa,
Sorry you were bummed out by the ending of Hunger Games. If you like binge material, check out Altered Carbon or Black Mirror on Netflix, they're¬† great!


Sincerely,

*Company name* Staff"
 
I sent them this, because they didn't think I was crazy/annoying enough yet:
"Oh, thanks! I will definitely watch those!
In the meantime, Team Peeta or Team Gale? (Or Team Haymitch)"
(I was on Team Gale, so no the Team Haymitch thing isn't serious. Actually, I got the idea from a Hunger Games interview I saw)

Needless to say, I didn't get a reply.
Eventually, I got impatient, and, at my best friend's urging, emailed them again, 20 days later (after finding the guy's name from the first email):
"Trevor, I'm sad. My friends have all ditched me, and I'm still upset that Gale ended up alone in crappy District 2.
And Katniss and Peeta's gross kids¬† exist!"
(For the millionth time, this isn't serious)
I have never gotten an email from them since.
1:19-1:20 Tom Haverford, is that you?

Ok James' idea to invest in hummus was undoubtedly a stroke of executive genius. I, a hummus lover, have conducted a small study. When I purchase a pot of hummus at my local Tesco, I always buy a pack of baby carrots to go with it (baby carrots because they're carrots but infinitely more swag). According to vigorous calculations, one pot of hummus is sufficient for approximately one and a half packs of baby carrots, so when I have consumed the pack I bought to accompany my hummus, I am left with a third of a pot of disappointment. So me, the lowly consumer, must spend more of my precious money on ANOTHER pack of baby carrots. Now of course I don't have nearly as much hummus as I did originally, so much less in fact that half of the new pack of baby carrots will be left without the appropriate dipping condiment. Now I can't possibly leave a perfectly good packet of baby carrots in my fridge staring back at me in shame every time I open it, so I am forced to buy yet another pot of hummus. With only half a pack of baby carrots left, you can see where this will inevitably lead me. The vicious cycle of hummus- capitalism continues

To the moron who titled this:
I'm pretty sure he said... SCAM emails,  not "spam".   There's a HUGE DIFFERENCE and I was wondering why his story sounded nothing like a "spam email".  Story. 

A "spam" email is an email like:  "click here for -> <whatever>"  and when you click you get either a virus or redirected towards some other site or source to supposedly get what you want or to provide your privacy details or whatever.  spams are mostly automated by a bot or some other similar program.  You can't converse with spam emails because often there's no one on the other side to respond.  Just an automated stuff to steal your details/money.

A SCAM is what you're hearing here: A guy approaches you either in real life, over the phone, or via email like here.. and pretends to offer money or reward in return for you providing money, yourself or details.

I've responded to spam with varying degrees of success. When I reply to scams of people who want me to send them money who will them send me money, my response is to say I'm totally willing to drop everything I am doing and fly to another country and help them with their problem if they either send me money or purchase tickets on my behalf.  Actually get responses to that, since I'm offering a compromise, but not for long. The other types of spam I never get responses to my responses.  For example,  I recently got a scam text telling me to verify my facebook account and it was relying on the use of subdomains to look legit, but anyone who knows how that works can see right through it so I said, "Nice try. For your efforts, I hereby curse you with eternal poverty." and there was no response,  but I do hope that it gave them chills. Not likely though since it's likely bot controlled and they'd only pay attention to information sent to their fake website.  My personal favorites are when I get emails telling me how I can increase my penis size, because I get to ask them if they have any products that decrease penis size instead on account of it being too big. No response to that either. lol

Bwahahaha! Brilliantly executed!  I played one of those scammers for months back in 2001. I worked for a Fortune 500 company, so I'd rather not name it, but it was very large and thus I had some empty offices with direct-line phone numbers and voicemails I could set up and use for my various "participants" in the transactions the scammer was so certain he'd suckered us into (I'd pulled two trustworthy coworkers/friends into my game).  It was great fun driving the guy completely insane and angering him to the point where he'd repeatedly call the numbers at all hours (I turned off the phones' ringers so nobody would hear during the day) and leave furious, almost incoherent voicemails.  He thought he was driving us mad with all the calls, and he acted so ridiculously high-and-mighty... but all he did was spend only-god-knows-how-much money on long distance calls from Nigeria.
All I have now are the amusing memories, sadly, because a now-ex-boyfriend turned out to be a narcissistic sociopath and during a tantrum one night (ignited while snooping through my computer while I was in the shower because since he was cheating on me, I must be cheating on him...because, you know, Sociopath Logic) he saw a photo of me posed with a small group of people, one of whom was male and had his arm around my shoulders. Instead of asking me about the photo, whereupon I could have suggested he look at the family resemblance, the date, etc and through other evidence provided proof that it was my cousin for chrissakes (and we're not a family inclined to incest), he went C-R-A-Z-Y and changed my email and social networking passwords (essentially stealing my accounts) and then deleted everything on my computer.  Just wiped the entire hard drive and all.  I never got any of it back, not even my accounts, because the Internet was even more lawless back then. üò°  I hope I get to witness (from a safe distance) karma destroying him!

One day I got an email from a certain girl who escaped from Senegal and was living in a refugee camp and was searching for a friend on the internet. She sent me photos that didn't appear to be fake, so I wondered why was it in my spam folder? It was just an innocent email! So I removed it from my spam folder and replied. The second email was fairlyweird though. She felt shecould trust me, so she told me her father died and she inherited lots of money, but because she hadn't been of legal age, she had no right to use the money, so she needed a money guardian. She wanted him to invest her money well. So yeah, I finally understood why it was in my spam folder. My next response?
iugfzgu
Surprisingly enough, I received a reply!! I was the chosen one! So she provided me with her birth certificate and death certificate of her dad (it is very funny that Senegal makes death certificates in English even for the natives) and wanted me to contact the lawyer she found. Well, I contacted him. He wanted my name, surname, address,... Well, simple answer. iggfjoi
In the end I had to tell the girl that there were certain fees in total of 650 dollars which I had to send to Bank of Scotland through Western Union. So I told her and she replied that she had no money with her, so I had to pay.
Well, I would have had paid happily. Unfortunately I had been a poor student and the study expenses had gotten me indebted so badly that my banker wasn't willing to lend me any money... But I desperately wanted to help that poor girl! Who was, btw, very cute. When the banker heard, he looked at her photos... And told me that he would lend me money if I could make her show him more... However, she replied that she was a pure Christian and she can't just send her nudes to anybody. Well... No nudes = no money. I just hope that pure soul found someone who helped her and got rich in the process... But well, I highly doubt it.

For anyone who doesn't know this scam: the tell you to go to your computer then they guide you to system log showing a string of messages that look like errors but are actually totally trivial. They then get you to give them remote access to your computer, they load some 'maintenance' software to 'stop the errors' (but actually to hide the log) then make you pay a monthly fee, typically about ¬£35. If you stop paying or disconect from the internet the 'maintenance software' corrupts the operating system and the victim's data.

Scambaiting is an enjoyable hobby which is also a good cause.  I highly recommend it.  

If you can string a scammer along, I suggest using some tools such as fake Western Union forms.  Google "scambaiting fake western union forms" and you'll see what I mean.  The forms are superficially real-looking but have silly questions and tasks for the scammer to perform.  I've gotten them to fill out the first page which looks like this:  http://s116.photobucket.com/user/nursenasty/media/wuform419a.jpg.html

Bait safely!  Don't ever divulge a real fact about yourself, no matter how innocuous.  Don't even send a fake ID to a scammer, as they will just use the image to scam someone else.  Use a separate email account which isn't liked to any of your other accounts.

If we just ignore them, we don't hurt them.... but if hundreds of thousand of people start to respond to these emails, they CAN'T possibly know which answers are fake, they can't filter it! So eventually they have to stop.

Let's do it!

Usually, people just get upset with spammers, cuss them out, and become grumpy for having to delete all the spam. But, Mr Veitch chose to use these spammy emails for his amusement rather than being frustrated.
